{{italic title}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}
'''''Arsti ramat nende juhhatamisseks kes tahtwad többed ärraarwada ning parrandada''''' ([[Estonian language|Estonian]] for ''Manual of medical diagnostics and healthcare'', literally ''Doctor's book to instruct those who want to guess and repair ailments'') was the first medical [[User guide|manual]] written in [[Estonian language|Estonian]] and is also regarded as the beginning of Estonian [[Popular science|popular-scientific]] literature.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sõukand|first=Renata|author2=Raal, Ain|date=October 2005|title=Data on Medicinal Plants in Estonian Folk Medicine: Collection, Formation and Overview of Previous Researches|journal=Folklore: Electronic Journal of Folklore|volume=30|pages=173–200|issn=1406-0949|publisher=Folk Belief and Media Group of Estonian Literary Museum|location=Tartu|url=http://www.folklore.ee/Folklore/vol30/soukand.pdf}}</ref>  It was compiled by [[Peter Ernst Wilde]], translated by [[August Wilhelm Hupel]] and printed in 1771.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utlib.ee/ekollekt/eeva/index.php?lang=en&do=tekst&tid=767|title=Arsti ramat (1771)|work=[[EEVA|Digital Text Repository for Older Estonian Literature]]|publisher=University of Tartu Library|accessdate=25 December 2009}}</ref>  It can be viewed as a continuation or a collection of their earlier work, the ''[[Lühhike öppetus]]''.

