[[File:Picturesque Europe.jpg|thumb|200px|The cover of one of the Cassell editions]] [[File:Picturesque Europe01.jpg|thumb|200px|''[[Capri]]'' by [[Harry Fenn]].]] {{italic title}} '''''Picturesque Europe''''' was a lavishly illustrated set of books published by [[D. Appleton & Co.]] in the mid-1870s based on their phenomenally successful ''[[Picturesque America]]''.{{sfnp|''Pict. Eur.''|1875|pp=iii–vi}} An edited form was reprinted in Europe by [[Cassell & Co.]]<ref>''Picturesque Europe'', [https://archive.org/details/picturesqueeurop01londuoft Cassell ed].</ref> The books depicted nature and tourist haunts in Europe, with text descriptions and numerous steel and wood engravings. [[Josiah Wood Whymper|J.W. Whymper]] was among the engravers and directed the other artists on the project.{{sfnp|Rainey & al.|1997|p=62}}
==Contents==
===Volume One=== Volume One covered the [[British Isles]], with unattributed articles on "[[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]]"; "[[Eton, Berkshire|Eton]]"; "[[North Wales]]"; "[[Warwick]] and [[Stratford-upon-Avon|Stratford]]"; "The South Coast, from [[Margate]] to [[Portsmouth]]"; "The [[Forests of the United Kingdom|Forest Scenery of Great Britain]]"; "The Dales of [[Derbyshire]]"; "[[Edinburgh]], and the South [[Lowlands of Scotland|Lowlands]]"; "[[Ireland]]"; "Scenery of the [[Thames]]"; "The South Coast, from [[Portsmouth]] to [[the Lizard]]<!--sic-->"; "English Abbeys and Churches"; "The [[Land's End]]"; "Old English Homes"; "The West Coast of Ireland"; "[[Welsh Marches|Border]] Castles and Counties"; "[[Cathedral city|Cathedral Cities]]"; "The [[Grampians]]"; "[[Oxford]]"; "[[Scotland]], from [[Loch Ness]] to [[Loch Eil]]"; "The West Coast of [[Wales]]"; and "The [[Lake Country]]".{{refn|group=n|Volumes I and II of the Cassell editions, which have identical text, credit these sections to T.G. Bonney; Oscar Browning; T.G. Bonney; T.G. Bonney; H.H.S. Pearse; W. Senior; T.G. Bonney; Jason Grant; John Francis Waller; W. Senior; T.G. Bonney; T.G. Bonney; T.G. Bonney;{{sfn|''Pict. Eur.'', Cassell ed., I|p=v}} H. Schütz Wilson; John Francis Waller; James Grant; T.G. Bonney; James Grant; Richard John King; James Grant; H. Schütz Wilson; and T.G. Bonney, respectively.{{sfn|''Pict. Eur'', Cassell ed., II|p=v}}}} These sections were illustrated with wood engravings of the drawings and paintings of [[William Henry James Boot|W.H.J. Boot]], C. Emery, [[Harry Fenn]], [[Henry Towneley Green|Towneley Green]], J. Harmsworth, C. Johnson, W.L. Jones, R.P. Leitch, W.W. May, J. North, [[Thomas Charles Leeson Rowbotham|T.L. Rowbotham]], T.D. Scott, E. Senior, P. Skelton, C.J. Staniland, E. Wagner, and [[Edmund Morison Wimperis|E.M. Wimperis]] and with a few steel engravings of the drawings and paintings of J. Chase, [[Harry Fenn]], [[Myles Birkett Foster|Birket Foster]], [[David Hall McKewan|D. McKewan]], [[William Leighton Leitch|W. Leitch]], [[John Mogford|J. Mogford]], S. Read, P. Skelton, and [[Edmund Morison Wimperis|E.M. Wimperis]].{{sfnp|''Pict. Eur.''|1875|pp=i–iv}}
===Volume Two=== Volume II covered more of Britain, as well as the [[Channel Islands]] and the [[European mainland|Continent]], with unattributed articles on "[[Cambridge]]"; "The South Coast of [[Devon]]shire"; "South [[Wales]]"; "North [[Devon]]"; "The [[Isle of Wight]]"; "[[Normandy]] and [[Brittany]]"; "The [[Lakes of Italy|Italian Lakes]]"; "The Passes of the [[Alps]]"; "The [[Cornice Road]]"; "The [[Forest of Fontainebleau]]"; "The [[Rhine]]"; "[[Venice]]"; "The [[Channel Islands]]"; "The [[Pyrenees]]"; "[[Rome]] and its Environs"; "The Bernese Oberland"; "The Rhine (from [[Boppart]] to the [[Drachenfels (Siebengebirge)|Drachenfels]])"; "[[Spain]] (The North and Old [[Castile and León|Castile]])"; "[[Auvergne (province)|Auvergne]] and [[Dauphiné]]"; "Old German Towns"; and "[[Naples]]".{{refn|group=n|Volumes II, III, & IV of the Cassell editions, which have identical text, credit these sections to T.G. Bonney; Richard John King; H. Schütz Wilson; Richard John King; H.H.S. Pearse;{{sfn|''Pict. Eur.'', Cassell ed., II|p=v}} Godfrey Wordsworth Turner; T.W. Hinchliff; T.G. Bonney; Oscar Browning; Godfrey Wordsworth Turner; R.J. King; T.G. Bonney;{{sfn|''Pict. Eur.'', Cassell ed., III|p=v}} W.H. Rideing;{{sfn|''Pict. Eur.'', Cassell ed., IV|p=v}} A. Griffiths; T.G. Bonney; T.G. Bonney; R.J. King; A. Griffiths;{{sfn|''Pict. Eur.'', Cassell ed., III|p=v}} T.G. Bonney; Oscar Browning; and T.G. Bonney, respectively.{{sfn|''Pict. Eur.'', Cassell ed., IV|p=v}}}} These sections were illustrated with wood engravings of the drawings and paintings of [[William Henry James Boot|W.H.J. Boot]], C. Emery, [[Harry Fenn]], [[Cyrus Johnson]], R.P. Leitch, W.W. May, T. Macquoid, [[Thomas Charles Leeson Rowbotham|T.L. Rowbotham]], E. Senior, P. Skelton, [[John Douglas Woodward (artist)|J.D. Woodward]], C. Whymper, and J. Wolf and with a few steel engravings of the drawings and paintings of S. Cook, [[Harry Fenn]], [[Myles Birkett Foster|Birket Foster]], [[Louis Haghe]], S.H. Hodson, G.G. Kilburne, [[Thomas Charles Leeson Rowbotham|T.L. Rowbotham]], [[Joseph B. Smith (artist)|J.B. Smith]], [[Carl Werner|C. Werner]], [[Edmund Morison Wimperis|E.M. Wimperis]], and L.J. Wood.{{sfnp|''Pict. Eur.''|1878|pp=i–iv}}
===Volume Three=== Volume III covered other parts of Europe: unattributed articles describe "[[Norway]]"; "[[Spain]] (New [[Castile-La Mancha|Castile]] and [[Extremadura|Estremadura]])"; "The [[Lake of Geneva]]"; "The Frontiers of [[France]] (East and South)"; "North [[Italy]]"; "[[Norway]] (The [[Sogne Fjord]], [[Nord Fjord]], [[Romsdal]])"; "[[Spain]] ([[Córdoba, Andalusia|Cordova]], [[Seville]], and [[Cadiz]])"; "The Frontiers of [[France]] (West and North)"; "[[Calabria]] and [[Sicily]]"; "The [[Black Forest]]"; "[[Sweden]]"; "The [[Tyrol–South Tyrol–Trentino Euroregion|Tyrol]]"; "[[Gibraltar]] and [[Ronda]]"; "[[Dresden]] and the [[Saxon Switzerland]]"; "Eastern [[Switzerland]]"; "[[Constantinople]]"; "[[Belgium]]"; "The [[High Alps]]"; "[[Granada]] and the East Coast of [[Spain]]"; "[[Russia]]"; "The [[Jura Mountains|Jura]]"; "[[Athens]] and its Environs"; "[[Holland]]"; and "The [[Danube]]".{{sfnp|''Pict. Eur.''|1879|pp=i–iv}}{{refn|group=n|Volumes IV and V of the Cassell editions, which have identical text, credit these sections to W. Mattieu Williams; Arthur Griffiths; T.W. Hinchliff; T.G. Bonney; T.G. Bonney; W. Mattieu Williams; Arthur Griffiths; Godfrey Wordsworth Turner; W. Mattieu Williams; George Adam Smith;{{sfn|''Pict. Eur.'', Cassell ed., IV|p=v}} Arthur Griffiths; T.G. Bonney; Arthur Griffiths; George Adam Smith; Arthur Griffiths; Percy Fitzgerald; T.G. Bonney; Arthur Griffiths; W.R.S. Ralston; G.F. Browne; W. Mattieu Williams; George Adam Smith; and George Adam Smith, respectively.{{sfn|''Pict. Eur.'', Cassell ed., V|p=v}}}} These sections were illustrated with wood engravings of the drawings and paintings of [[William Henry James Boot|W.H.J. Boot]], E. Compton, [[Harry Fenn]], W. Herbert, R.P. Leitch, E. Senior, P. Skelton, C.J. Staniland, J. Williams, and [[John Douglas Woodward (artist)|J.D. Woodward]] and with a few steel engravings of the drawings and paintings of E. Compton, [[Harry Fenn]], [[Myles Birkett Foster|Birket Foster]], E. George,